OHAP. LXXXI.

Some history of Tiberias. The Jerusalem Talmud was written there ; ancl when.

TIBERIASb was built by Herod the tetrarch in honour of Tiberius: and that in a common burying-place, or in a place where many sepulchres had been. Hence it was that the founder was fain to use all manner of persuasion‚ entice- ments, and liberality, to invite inhabitants. The very de- lightful situation of the place seemed to put him on to wrestle with such a difficulty and inconvenience‚ rat-her than not to enjoy so pleasant a soil and seat. For on this side, the sea washing upon it,—on that side, within a little way, Jordan gliding by it‚—on the other side, the hot baths of Ghannnath, —and on another, the most fruitful country Gennesaret ad- jacent‚—did every way begird this city, when it was builtC, with pleasure and delight.
